sion entity: :recon/trace-336f7289e725a988; What connects t-56363369 to t-f12bff46?; What connects t-56363369 to t-6094?; What connects t-56363369 to t-6094?; Session entity: :recon/trace-495b6b436e9b735b; What connects t-56363369 to t-f12bff46?; What connects t-56363369 to t-6094?; Session entity: :config/concept-join-threshold; What connects t-56363369 to t-6094?; What connects t-56363369 to t-f12bff46?; Session entity: :recon/trace-62737c2784fe7303; Session entity: :recon/trace-3cbc0666d81812a2; Session entity: :recon/trace-f2752db320441572; Session entity: :task/t-b39ad7cb; Session entity: :task/t-1d8338a1; What connects t-56363369 to t-6094?; Session entity: :recon/trace-af087560901db86a; Session entity: :config/concept-sigmoid-temperature; What connects t-56363369 to t-f12bff46?; Session entity: :config/calibration-similarity-count; Session entity: :config/calibration-similarity-sum; What connects t-56363369 to t-6094?\nCATEGORY-THEORETIC FOUNDATION: In the ISP triangle, morphisms I->S->P are formalization and implementation. The unified store model (ADR-TRILATERAL-001) realizes these as entity set membership: entity e in I intersect S means the formalization morphism maps that intent to a spec. Entity e in S intersect P means the implementation morphism maps that spec to code. This is the natural model for a unified store — entities SPAN boundaries rather than being linked ACROSS boundaries by separate Ref links. Ref links (:spec/depends-on, :impl/implements) capture STRUCTURAL DEPENDENCIES between entities, which is orthogonal to ISP coverage. The distinction: coverage = 'has this intent been formalized?' (set membership). Dependency = 'does this spec depend on that spec?' (Ref graph). These answer different questions and should use different mechanisms.; PROFILING RESULT: braid status at 183K datoms takes 3.1s in release. Breakdown: routing=155ms, snapshot=184ms, projection=2557ms. Within projection: boundaries=2407ms (94%), concepts=57ms, FEGH=41ms, methodology=37ms, action=12ms. Root cause: formality_level() in trilateral.rs:282 uses store.datoms().filter(entity==) — O(N) per entity, called per boundary gap (~170 gaps). 170 * 183K = 31M iterations. Fix: use store.entity_datoms(entity) (EAVT-indexed, O(entity_datoms)). This is Phase A task A2.; Session entity: :task/t-32d5c980; DETECTION FAILURE ANALYSIS: This is an FM-010 class failure (Spec Self-Contradiction). SEED.md §3 designed 5-tier contradiction detection: Tier 1 (Exact) — IMPLEMENTED, checks same (e,a) with different values. Tier 2 (Logical) — PARTIALLY IMPLEMENTED (2/4 rules: polarity inversion, numeric bound). Tier 3 (Semantic) — NOT IMPLEMENTED — would catch 'formula assumes Ref, schema says String'. Tier 4 (Pragmatic) — NOT IMPLEMENTED. Tier 5 (Axiological) — post-hoc only via braid challenge. The bilateral K (Contradiction) component has weight 0.13 in F(S) but only runs Tiers 1-2. K defaults to 0 for semantic contradictions, making F(S) insensitive to this failure class. Three mechanisms would have caught it: (1) Tier 3 cross-check of formula type assumptions vs schema, (2) hypothesis ledger tests for Phi against known-good stores, (3) braid challenge on INV-TRILATERAL-002.; SPEC CONTRADICTION: spec/18-trilateral.md line 74 formula defines D_IS = |{e in LIVE_I | not-exists link: link.a = :spec/traces-to AND link.v = e}| — this assumes Ref semantics (link.v = e matches Value to EntityId). But spec/02-schema.md line 158 declares :spec/traces-to as ValueType::String. The formula is not mechanizable given the schema. Commentary at lines 81-84 says 'String presence, not Ref entity resolution' — contradicting the formula itself. This is a Tier 3 (Semantic) contradiction: two spec elements (INV-TRILATERAL-002 and the schema definition) make irreconcilable type assumptions about the same attribute. In production, compute_phi could never find Ref values for :spec/traces-to, so D_IS always equaled |LIVE_I| — every intent entity was counted as a gap regardless of formalization status. Phi was structurally broken for all stores with intent entities.; Phase A computation target MET: routing=155ms + snapshot=184ms + projection=500ms = 840ms total computation. Under 1s target. Wall clock 3.06s dominated by store loading (~2s bincode). Daemon amortizes store loading — daemon response should be well under 1s. Key fix: formality_level O(N)->O(entity_datoms) reduced boundaries from 2407ms to 11ms. Single highest-impact optimization in the session.; LEGACY COMPATIBILITY: Existing stores contain ~113 :spec/traces-to Ref datoms created by prior spec_dependency_datoms() calls. C1 (append-only) means these cannot be deleted. Strategy: dual-read in topology coupling and spec_graph_neighbors reads both :spec/depends-on AND legacy :spec/traces-to Ref datoms. compute_beta_1 reads only :spec/depends-on (losing legacy edges temporarily until next braid topology deps run generates equivalent edges). No migration needed — legacy datoms are technically schema-violating (String type has Ref value) but the append-only store tolerates them.; SCHEMA CARDINALITY MISMATCH: spec/02-schema.md line 158 declares :spec/traces-to as String :many multi. But schema.rs line 1223 implements it as attr() (Cardinality::One), not attr_multi(). The spec says a spec element can trace to multiple SEED sections; the implementation allows only one. This is a second contradiction within the same attribute — type AND cardinality are both misaligned between spec and implementation.; IMPLEMENTATION GAP: :spec/depends-on is defined in spec/02-schema.md line 159 as 'Ref :many multi — X requires Y (sequencing constraint)' but is NOT in schema.rs. The topology module's spec_dependency_datoms() (topology.rs:830) works around this by writing structural dependency Ref links to :spec/traces-to instead — wrong attribute, wrong type. This function parses :element/traces-to String values, extracts spec IDs (INV-*, ADR-*), resolves to EntityIds, and creates Ref datoms. These should be :spec/depends-on datoms. The function bypasses schema validation via Store::from_datoms, so the type mismatch doesn't error at transaction time.; LOOP CLOSURE STRATEGY (ADR-FOUNDATION-014): Three interventions to prevent recurrence. (1) IMMEDIATE: Add bilateral-verified hypothesis tests for spec formulas. Test Phi against known-good stores (genesis, fully-linked entity, intent-only entity). Uses existing hypothesis infrastructure. (2) MEDIUM-TERM: Implement Tier 3 semantic detection in coherence.rs. Rule: when spec formula text references attribute name, verify assumed type matches schema. Attribute names have distinctive :namespace/name pattern. (3) LONG-TERM: Wire Tier 3+ into bilateral K component so F(S) decreases when semantic contradictions exist, guidance surfaces them, convergence engine recommends resolution. Each intervention closes one more sub-loop of the open detection gap.; PRE-EXISTING BUG: 2 braid CLI tests fail on clean main (before ISP-FIX): ready_excludes_blocked and create_task_with_valid_spec_ref_produces_traces_to. Root cause: Session 049 introduced generate_task_id_full (content-addressed from title+description+priority+type) but tests use generate_task_id (which defaults priority=2) while creating tasks with different priorities (0, 1). ID mismatch → task not found. Fix: use generate_task_id_full with matching parameters in tests.; FEEDBACK MODE: This failure is itself a data point for braid's calibration machinery. The hypothesis ledger (hypothesis/* attributes, record_hypotheses(), compute_calibration_metrics()) was designed to catch exactly this: record what Phi SHOULD produce for known stores, measure what it ACTUALLY produces. Mean error is 0.529 and degrading — Phi's structural brokenness likely contributes. Specific hypotheses that would have caught it: (1) Phi(genesis) should equal 0 — passes trivially (no intent entities). (2) Phi(entity with intent+spec+impl attrs) should equal 0 — would have FAILED, exposing the bug. (3) Phi(intent-only entity) should be positive — passes but for wrong reasons (would pass even with the broken implementation). Hypothesis (2) is the discriminating test.; Session entity: :task/t-b3873e87; CONSISTENCY GAP: check_coherence (full) and check_coherence_fast computed Phi differently. check_coherence_fast used entity set membership (correct). check_coherence used compute_phi which tried Ref-link-based coverage (broken). isp_check and formality_level also use entity set membership. So 3 of 4 ISP functions used the correct model — only compute_phi was wrong. The set-membership model uses MaterializedViews ISP entity sets (O(1) lookup) instead of O(N) datom scans, making the fix also a performance improvement. This directly serves Phase A Wave 3 (session-050 critical path).; THREE ORTHOGONAL TRACEABILITY LEVELS: The ISP model conflates three distinct concepts into :spec/traces-to. Level 1 (Entity Coverage): set membership — entity e in LIVE_I intersect LIVE_S means intent formalized. Used by Phi, isp_check, formality_level, check_coherence_fast. Level 2 (Textual Provenance): :spec/traces-to String — 'SEED §4', 'C1'. Records why a spec element exists. Audit trails, formality gradient. Level 3 (Structural Dependency): :spec/depends-on Ref — links between spec entities for ordering, coupling, cycle detection. Used by beta_1, topology. These three levels are orthogonal. The bug was conflating Level 1 (gap computation) with Level 2 (textual provenance) and conflating Level 2 with Level 3 (storing Ref values in a String attribute).; PERFORMANCE: formality_level O(N)->O(entity) fix reduced braid status from 5.95s to 3.58s user CPU (40% reduction). Single line change: store.datoms().filter(entity==) to store.entity_datoms(entity). Remaining 3.5s still dominated by boundary evaluation. Next targets: forward_scan/backward_scan redundant live_projections calls, observation_boundary datom scan." :op :assert}
